interesting choice.. I wouldn't call everyone using openbmc a service provider. 

How about openbmc companies?

Or just reword completely something more like 

Converting to an enum and adding a "NotSupported" value allows this property to not show for implementations that don't support it.
This doesn't work. Can you just link: https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/46886 ?
I removed my manual edit and now it seems to work and point at the right discussion link
this is an xyz.openbmc_project interface, so no need to mention PEL ehre.
I believe this paragraph needs to be updated.
Exhibit doesn't quite feel appropriate here.  How about a simple Yes/No?

As per the comment here ...https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/47683/7/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Logging/Entry.interface.yaml#101, I removed the NotNotifed enum. I will change Exhibit to Notify,
Please capitalize to match enum name.

I would suggest dropping this or changing to "requires a service action to correct the event, such as replacing the hardware part or updating code."

We should also be careful about mixing the words "event" and "error".  Is this an error or an event?
alternatively:  The service provider should not be notified about the event log.
Minor comments but seems reasonable to me.

This reads kind of weird, maybe something more like:

If this property value is set to 'Notify', the service provider must be notified. 

or

If this property value is set to 'Notify', the service provider must be notified about the Entry.
I don't understand why this sentence is needed but it isn't new so 🤷.
Added you to the ibm/ci-authorized gerrit group. Already on IBM's CCLA.
